\layout Section

Executive Summary
\layout Standard

The purpose of this report was to compare three different companies and
 evaluate them as potential employers.
 The companies selected are actual companies for whom I am considering working.
 These companies include Healthcare.com, Not a Number, and the Automated
 Trading Desk.
\layout Standard

Research was done on the three companies, and information was gathered from
 the company's website, from an Internet search engine, and from interviews
 with employees at the company (in the case of Not a Number, this was not
 possible).
\layout Standard

Many different criteria were evaluated.
 Monetary benefits such as salary and stock options were considered, though
 non-monetary benefits such as attending conferences and personal development
 were also considered.
 Other information, such as the products the company produces, were also
 looked at.
\layout Standard

Though each of the three companies would be a great place to work, the Automated
 Trading Desk was evaluated as the most elligible potential employeer.
 ATD has the greatest benefits, and does very challenging and interesting
 work.
\layout Section

Introduction
\layout Standard

The purpose of this report is to compare three companies for which jobs
 may be available.
 This is in order that, when the time comes, an objective comparison can
 be made between the companies as to which is the best company to work for.
\layout Standard

The scope of this document is limited, as the companies being compared are
 companies for whom I am considering working.
 Only qualities of the company are compared; no job characteristics are
 being considered.
 None of the companies compared are being considered as lifelong positions.
\layout Standard

The tree companies being compared include:
\layout Itemize

Healthcare.com
\layout Itemize

Not a Number
\layout Itemize

Automated Trading Desk
\layout Standard

Healthcare.com is actually an alias for the Center for Computing and Information
 Technology, which runs all the computer systems at the Medical University
 of South Carolina.
 The work done is all outsourced, and healthcare.com currently holds the
 contract with MUSC.
 When I previously worked for CCIT, the contract was first with Coleman
 Research Corporation and then with Thermo Information Systems.
 Though the contract has now been sold, the job requirements and the work
 environment remain the same.
\layout Standard

Not A Number, which is located in Amsterdam, is famous among the graphics
 community for Blender, their modeling and animation package.
 Though it was crippleware (software which is crippled until the user enters
 a special key, which costs money) during the time in which it was being
 developed, it is now free software.
 Though this may seem to an economist a bad business practice, providing
 a free service to the community is a great way to get cheap (and more important
ly, effective) advertisement; Not a Number receives over a million hits
 to their webpage monthly.
\layout Standard

The Automated Trading Desk was started about three years ago in a garage
 when someone got the idea to hook up a computer to a satellite feed of
 stock market information.
 The company has expanded to using computer models to predict the market
 using the real-time data coming from the feed.
 The computer models are given freedom to make stock trades by themselves,
 and seem to do a very good job at doing so.
 In 1999, ATD reported $3 million revenue per employee.
